Q. How does IaaS work?
â˜… IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service) provides virtual infrastructure (like VMs, storage,
network) but you manage everything above it â€” like the OS, middleware, and
applications.
â˜… Data - data inside services (like VMs) is not automatically persisted.
â˜… Services are mostly stateless(wont persist data). Why?
â˜… To enable scalability â€” easily add/remove instances without losing data.
â˜… So you must externalize the data
â˜… external database store in redis,memcache (no sql) - key value pair db
â˜… if u r storing by urself -> u have to take care of that
Q. Why Services Don't Store Data by Themselves?
â— To scale easily and avoid data loss.
â— Example: During an Amazon flash sale, 10,000+ people may add laptops
to their cart, and backend servers need to scale instantly. If services
store data inside themselves, new servers start fresh and old data is lost,
but if they're stateless and use external databases, all instances share
the same data, enabling seamless scaling and consistent user
experience.
Q. Beneits of IaaS?
â–  ğŸ’¸ Cost Reduction
No need to invest in physical infrastructure. Pay-as-you-go model helps cut
upfront costs.
â˜… âš¡ Faster Deployment (Automated)
Automation tools enable faster provisioning, testing, and releasing â€” reduces
time-to-market.
â˜… ğŸ” High Availability & Reliability
Use of AMIs (Amazon Machine Images) ensures reliable replication and fast
recovery in case of failures.
â˜… ğŸŒ Global Reach
Easily deploy applications in any region around the world to serve users with low
latency.
â˜… ğŸ” Data Security and Compliance
Data can be encrypted and moved to specific regions to comply with local
regulations and standards.
Q. Challenges of Iaas?
â— Security & Vulnerabilities
Cloud platforms may face vulnerabilities â€” providers send alerts, but you must apply patches
yourself (especially in IaaS).
â— Compliance Requirements
Industries like banking and healthcare (e.g., HIPAA in the US) require strict data confidentiality.
â—‹ In SaaS, data is with the provider.
â—‹ In IaaS, you are responsible for compliance and data protection.
â—‹ compliance -> banking , medical
â—‹ in us and europe - u need to give ur critical info to doc,so data is confidential..cant
shared
â—‹ hippa complaints - hippa guidelines - followed by us
â—‹ if using saas, they have data
â—‹ iaas - ur responsibility
â— Integration with Existing Systems
Old systems (legacy apps) may not work smoothly with new cloud or automation tools â€” so
extra effort or changes may be needed to make them work together.
â— Dependency on Cloud Provider
Service interruptions, pricing changes, or policy shifts by the provider can impact your business.
