Strategy vs Tactics
â” Strategy â†’ Long-term plan (vision-level)
â” Tactics â†’ Short-term steps to solve specific problems (especially NFRs)
â” NFR(Non Functional Requirements) -
â—† Example: Incoming event â†’ system processes â†’ outgoing response
â” large number of events(like req) - cause performance issues
â” solving NFR issues have tactics
â” tactics for solving performance and tactics for solving Scalability is diff
â” Tactic for Performance: Use Redis caching, enable GZIP compression.
â” Tactic for Scalability: Use Kubernetes HPA + Azure Load Balancer.
Scalability
â” Ability of the system to handle increasing load gracefully
â” Load increases â†’ more users, requests, events
â” Resources can become constrained â†’ CPU, memory, DB connections
â” Can cause latency, timeouts, or crashes if not handled
â” Solution : horizontal scaling(more machines),Auto-scaling(based on CPU, memory, request
count),distribute load equally by load balancer.
Q. why iaas is more vulnerable than paas and saas?
You manage the entire OS, patches, security groups, firewall rules, etc. A small misconfiguration
(like leaving SSH open to the world) can expose your system. Attackers exploit weak IAM policies,
open buckets, default credentials, etc.
Buildtime vs Runtime
â” Build time : ok to take more time to build
â” Build Time â†’
â—† Time taken to create Docker image
â—† Okay if it takes more time (once per deployment)
â—† Image Caching helps here (layers reused)
â—† image caching helps in build time not run time
â” Solution:
â” Use Multi-stage Builds
â—† Only copy the required final binaries into the production image
â—† Means - After building your app, just take the output file (like a .jar, .pyc, or built
folder) and put only that into the final Docker image.
â—† Donâ€™t include: Source code,Build tools,Temporary files
â—† Final binaries - These are the files that are ready to run.
â” Use small base image
â—† (alpine -they have networking)
â—† So that attack surfaces reduces
â” Run time:Time when the app is running in production
â—† Affects performance and user experience
â—† Image caching doesnâ€™t help here
