Q. NAT Gateway?
â” You created a private subnet
â” VMs inside this cannot be accessed from the internet.
â” To allow these VMs to go out to internet, you need a NAT Gateway
PRACTICAL:
â— created virtual network with ip range 10.1.0.0/16 for front-end
â— Back-end = 10.1.1.0
â— Private = 10.1.2.0

1. Created a VNet with 3 subnets:
â—‹ Frontend Subnet (Public)
â—‹ Backend Subnet (Public â€” but no Public IP assigned)
â—‹ Private Subnet
2. Virtual Machines
â— Frontend VM
â—‹ Subnet: Frontend
â—‹ Public IP assigned âœ…
â—‹ Can SSH from internet
â— Backend VM
â—‹ Subnet: Backend
â—‹ No Public IP âŒ
â—‹ Used for internal communication
â— Private VM
â—‹ Subnet: Private
â—‹ No Public IP âŒ
â—‹ Intended to be completely private (internal access only)
ğŸ”¹ 3. Network Security Groups (NSGs): Defining who can access what
ğŸ”¸ Created 3 Separate NSGs:
â— Frontend NSG
â— Backend NSG
â— Private NSG
ğŸ”¸ Associations:
â— Frontend NSG â†’ Associated with Frontend VM
â— Backend NSG â†’ Associated with Backend VM
â— Private NSG â†’ Associated with Private VM
ğŸ”¹ 4. NetworkSecurityGroup Rules
âœ… Frontend + Backend (Public) Subnets:
â— Inbound Rule:
â—‹ Source: *
â—‹ Destination Port Ranges: *
â—‹ Action: Allow
â—‹ Priority: Default or custom (lower number)
Allows general access from any source (for demo/testing).
âœ… Private Subnet Rules (Important):
â— ğŸŸ© Allow from Backend:
â—‹ Priority: 100 (higher priority means evaluated first)
â—‹ Source: Backend subnet or IP
â—‹ Action: Allow
â— ğŸŸ¥ Deny All Rule:
â—‹ Priority: 200 (lower than allow rule, so checked after)
â—‹ Source: *
â—‹ Destination Port Ranges: *
â—‹ Action: Deny
ğŸ” This setup only allows traffic from Backend to Private VM, blocks everything else.
Note:
â” Copied the pemfile into frontend,backend and private.
â” For copy : scp -i pemfile pemfile username@ipaddress:/home/username
â” Then try to connect using ssh to frontend
â” After connection,connect to backend from frontend using privateip of backend
â” After that try to connect to private
Q. communication happen in public domain encrypted or not?
â” Yes ., communication in the public domain is encrypted, if you're using secure protocols.
â” Ssh - encrypted using pem file
â” When going over the internet (e.g., Cloud Shell â†’ VM), encryption happens via SSH.
â” Communication between VMs inside a VNet is private, not exposed to the public
internet.â€™
â” So yes, communication is encrypted in the public domain if you're using the right
protocols like HTTPS or SSH.
Q. BGP?- Border Gateway Protocol
â” BGP is a routing protocol used to exchange routing info between different networks
â” Finds best path
â” Azure uses BGP for hybrid networking, like when connecting your on-premise network to
Azure using VPN Gateway or ExpressRoute.
â” Protocol runs the internet
