Q. Azure Global Infrastructure?
Azure Global Infrastructure refers to the complete network of
â” data centers,
â” regions,
â” availability zones, and connectivity components
Microsoft uses to deliver Azure cloud services across the world.
â˜… Regions: Specific geographic areas (e.g., Central India, East US) with Azure data centers.
â˜… Availability zones: Separate data centers within a region for high availability. If one zone fails,
others stay up.
â˜… Regional Pairs: Two regions paired (e.g., Mumbai-Hyderabad) for disaster recovery. One fails,
traffic moves to the other.
â˜… More regions: Azure has more regions globally than AWS (including Mumbai and Hyderabad
in India).
â˜… Edge location : Small data centers close to users (in different parts of the world) to deliver
content quickly.
â—‹ CDN(content delivery Network): A network of servers that deliver content (images,
videos, etc.) faster to users.
â—‹ Reduces traffic to main servers and loads content faster for the user.
â—‹ You visit a website â†’ it wants to load an image
â—‹ Instead of sending your request to the main server in US,
â—‹ It checks the nearest Edge Location (e.g., in India)
â—‹ If image is already stored (cached) there â†’ it downloads it instantly
â—‹ Result: Faster page load, less delay, less internet traffic
Q. Key aspects of cloud region?
â” Geographic Location:
â—† The physical location where the cloud data centers are placed.
â” Multiple Data Centers (DC):
â—† A region has more than one data center to ensure high availability and backup.
â” Isolation:
â—† One region doesn't affect the other if something fails â€” safe and independent.
â” Low Latency:
â—† Closer region = faster response time (less delay in getting your data).
