Q. when you create the group,the membership type becomes assigned. Then what happens?
â” When you create a group in Azure Entra ID (formerly Azure AD), the membership type
depends on your license level:
â—† Assigned Membership (Free / Default)
â— You manually add or remove users to the group.
â— Available in Free tier.
â—† Dynamic Membership (P1 or P2 required)
â— Users are added/removed automatically based on rules (like department,
location, etc.).
â— Available in Azure AD Premium P1 and P2.
â— Example: user.department == "IT" â†’ Auto-added to "IT Team" group.
â” it will change in p1 nd p2-(dynamic)
â” dynamic membership becomes available only if your tenant has P1 or P2 license.
â” Otherwise, it stays as Assigned.
Q.forecast and actual in azure budgets?
â” Forecast::
â—† The forecast is an estimate of how much you will spend on Azure services based on
historical data and trends.
â—† Example: Letâ€™s say in the last month, you used Azure services worth $100. Based on that
usage, Azure predicts that you will spend around $120 in the next month based on your
usage patterns. This prediction is the forecast.
â” Actual:
â—† The actual amount is the real cost youâ€™ve incurred so far for Azure services.
â—† Example: After 15 days into the next month, you check your actual usage and find that
you have already spent $60 on Azure services. This is your actual spending up to that
point.
Q. Vnet pairing practical?
â” create vnet using azure client
â” Login to Azure CLI:
â—† az login
â” Create Virtual Networks (VNets):
â—† Creating 2 vnets of diff range of ip to do vnet pairing
â—† First vnet:
â— az network vnet create --resource-group abhi-resource-group --name abhi-vnet
--address-prefixes 10.3.0.0/16
â—† 2nd vnet:
â— az network vnet create --resource-group abhi-resource-group --name abhi-vnet2
--address-prefixes 10.4.0.0/16
â” Create Subnets:
â—† For each VNet, create subnets to define the network structure.
â—† Create subnet for abhi-vnet:
â— az network vnet subnet create --resource-group abhi-resource-group
--vnet-name abhi-vnet --name abhi-subnet --address-prefix 10.3.0.0/16
â—† Create subnet for abhi-vnet2:
â— az network vnet subnet create --resource-group abhi-resource-group
--vnet-name abhi-vnet2 --name abhi-subnet --address-prefix 10.4.0.0/16
â” Create Virtual Machines (VMs):
â—† create VMs in each of the VNets to test connectivity between them.
â—† Create VM in abhi-vnet:
â— az vm create --resource-group abhi-resource-group --name abhi-vm --location
centralindia --image Ubuntu2204 --size Standard_B1s --vnet-name abhi-vnet
--subnet abhi-subnet --admin-username abhi --admin-password abhi@12345678
â—† Create VM in abhi-vnet2:
â— az vm create --resource-group abhi-resource-group --name abhi-vm2 --location
centralindia --image Ubuntu2204 --size Standard_B1s --vnet-name abhi-vnet2
--subnet abhi-subnet --admin-username abhi --admin-password abhi@12345678
â— If you face a quota error (insufficient resources), request a quota increase for the
Central India region.
â” Connect to VMs Using SSH:
â—† ssh abhi@<public-ip-of-abhi-vm>
â—† ssh abhi@<public-ip-of-abhi-vm2>
â—† Test if you can ping one VM from the other using their public IPs.
â” Ping from VM1 to VM2:
â—† ping <public-ip-of-abhi-vm2>
â” Set Up VNet Peering:
â—† You need to configure VNet peering in both VNets so they can communicate with each
other.
â—† Peer abhi-vnet with abhi-vnet2:
â— az network vnet peering create --name abhi-peering --resource-group
abhi-resource-group --vnet-name abhi-vnet --remote-vnet abhi-vnet2
--allow-vnet-access
â—† Peer abhi-vnet2 with abhi-vnet (you need to create peering in both directions):
â— az network vnet peering create --name abhi-peering --resource-group
abhi-resource-group --vnet-name abhi-vnet2 --remote-vnet abhi-vnet
--allow-vnet-access
â” Test Private IP Connectivity:
â—† After VNet peering is established, try to ping the VMs using their private IPs.
â—† Ping from VM1 to VM2 using Private IP:
â— ping <private-ip-of-abhi-vm2>
â—† Ping from VM2 to VM1 using Private IP:
â— ping <private-ip-of-abhi-vm>
