Q. . Why Use Service Principals Instead of Users?
â” If access is given directly to a user, and that user leaves or is removed, the service breaks.
â” Service Principals are non-human identities created specifically for apps or services.
â—† They provide a stable identity for services to authenticate and access resources.
â—† Managed by Azure AD.
Q. Management Group?
â” A container for subscriptions.
â” You can assign roles at this level to control access across multiple subscriptions.
â” Subscription:
â” Contains resources and is tied to billing.
â” subscription will be in tenant group
â” Can have different subscription for diff management groups
â” subscription within tenant associated to payment
â” You can have multiple subscriptions in a tenant, useful for separating environments (prod, dev,
etc.).
Q. Microsoft Entra ID ?
â” Identity and Access Management (IAM) service from Microsoft.
â” Manages users, groups, service principals, roles, devices, etc.
â” active directory to maintain identity
â” It helps with authentication (verifying users) and authorization (giving users the right access to
resources).
â” user management,access to management users -not treated as resources
â” They are more like security objects that help manage access and roles across Azure resources.
â” You do not need subscription-level permissions to create users or groups. These are controlled
at the Azure AD level (not subscription level).
â” Permissions for user management are controlled by roles assigned to users within Azure AD.
Q. user administrator vs global administrator?
1. User Administrator:
â” Primary Focus: Manage users and groups within Azure AD.
â” Permissions:
â—† Create, Update, Delete users.
â—† Reset passwords for users.
â—† Create, Update, Delete groups.
â” Assign users to roles but with restricted access to global settings.
2. Global Administrator:
â” Can manage all aspects of Microsoft Entra ID and Microsoft services that use Microsoft Entra
identities.
â” Primary Focus: Full administrative control over Azure AD and all Microsoft services tied to
Entra identities.
â” Complete access to all aspects of Azure AD: manage users, roles, security policies, and
configurations.
â” Can configure enterprise-level settings, such as conditional access, multi-factor
authentication, and directory settings.
Q. Eventual Consistency:
â” This is a model where, over time, a system will become consistent, but there may be temporary
states where data is inconsistent. In other words, the system doesnâ€™t guarantee immediate
consistency after each update, but eventually, all nodes (or replicas) will converge to the same
state.
â” eg:Amazon Payments: If you purchase an item, the payment status might not be immediately
reflected across all systems. For example, while one system says â€œpayment pending,â€ another
system may say â€œpayment processed.â€ Over time, these systems will sync, and the data will
become consistent, but there's no guarantee of immediate consistency.
â” Eg: nosql database
Q. ACID Properties (for Relational Databases):?
Atomicity:
â” Either all parts of the transaction are completed, or none of them are.
â” If youâ€™re transferring money from Bank A to Bank B, the transaction will either:
â— Fully complete (money deducted from Bank A, added to Bank B), or
â— Rollback if any part fails (like a system crash).
â— If the transfer fails midway (e.g., money withdrawn from A but not deposited in
B), the system ensures that the transaction is rolled back to its initial state.
Consistency:
â” A database must move from one valid state to another valid state. The data must always meet
the rules or constraints defined for the database (e.g., foreign keys, data types).
â” Example: If you write data to the database, the data should be consistent with the database's
rules. For instance, if you try to store a negative value in a column that only allows positive
numbers, the database will reject it.
â” Whatever written = whatevr reading.
â” NoSQL (e.g., Cassandra, DynamoDB) focuses on eventual consistency, where data may be
inconsistent temporarily but will eventually become consistent across all nodes.
Isolation:
â” Definition: Transactions should be isolated from each other. Even if multiple transactions are
happening at the same time, they should not interfere with each otherâ€™s operations.
â” Isolation levels:
â—† Read Uncommitted: Transactions can read uncommitted changes.
â—† Read Committed: Only committed changes are visible.
â—† Repeatable Read: The data read by a transaction cannot be changed by other
transactions.
â—† Serializable: The highest level, ensuring that transactions are executed serially (one
after the other).
â—† Example: If two users are trying to withdraw money at the same time, isolation ensures
that one transaction doesnâ€™t interfere with the other.
Durability:
â” Definition: Once a transaction is committed, it is permanent, even in the case of a
system crash.
â” Example: If a transaction to update a bank balance is committed, the change is saved,
and even if the database crashes immediately afterward, the transaction will not be lost.
Q. Primary,Secondary,Territory -related to databases?
â” Primary:
The main database instance where all write operations happen first.
â” Secondary:
A copy of the primary; it syncs data from the primary and can be used for reading (depending on
the setup).
â” Tertiary:
Another replica â€” basically a third copy to add even more redundancy.
â” Read Replica:
A replica used only for read queries to reduce load on the primary. Updates from the primary are
asynchronously synced.
Q. . NoSQL Database â€“ Sharding?
â” Breaking a large database into smaller parts (shards) to distribute across multiple machines.
Example:
â” Shard 1 â†’ keys a - e
â” Shard 2 â†’ keys f - j
â” And so on.
â” Replication Rules:
â” Replica stored on at least two other machines:
Every piece of data is stored not just on the primary node, but also on at least 2 other nodes (for
fault tolerance).
â” Transaction commits - n/2 + 1 instances written:
For a transaction to be considered successful:
â—† It must be written to more than half the nodes.
â—† If there are n total replicas, at least (n/2) + 1 must acknowledge.
Eventually Consistent Sync
â— Eventual Consistency:
The replicas might not be immediately consistent after a write,
but over time, all copies will have the same data.
