Q. some imp commands:
â” cd .terraform/tab/tab
â—† Where the latest provider plugins are downloaded
â” .terraform.lock.hcl file
â—† terraform is never be backward compatible
â” because it has to work with cloud provider
â” Cloud providers keep updating their services, so Terraform must update too.
â” If you already wrote some code and Terraform updates modules, your old code might break
(because of new changes).
â” To protect you:
â—† Terraform creates a lock file (.terraform.lock.hcl) to freeze the versions you are
using.
â—† Unless you manually force an update, Terraform keeps using the old (locked)
versions.
â—† Even if you remove version from your .tf code, Terraform still knows the version from
the lock file.
â—† Only if you delete lock file or force an update, it will pick new versions.
â—† Lock file = Safety net to prevent breaking your working Terraform code when
providers change.
â” When you do cat .terraform.lock.hcl (to view it):
â” You will see the version number of the provider/module you are using
â” The rest of the content is in hashed format (for security and integrity checking).
â” Even if you remove the provider version from your .tf code file,
â” Terraform will still remember the version from the lock file.
â” It won't automatically upgrade unless you delete or update the lock file.
â” Terraform plan
â” Its like database execution plan
â” whenever u r executing any query - do execution plan
â” analyze the best way to execute - improve performance
â” analyze code and do whatever need to go
â—† modify -golden
â—† remove -red
â—† added -green
â” Id will be know only after we apply the terraform
â” so review this and apply
â” After reviewing the plan â” run terraform apply to actually create/update/delete
resources.
â” If you want to save the plan and reuse it without re-planning:
â” output this as a file and pass this as parameter to apply
â” You can skip manual approval by using:
â—† terraform apply -auto-approve
Q. when all it compares with the 3 things(.tf file,cloud,.tf state file)?
â” Plan
â” Apply
â” destroy
Q. why do we need to create a plan file?
â” Plan file = freeze the changes you reviewed, then safely apply them later.
â” Terraform always compares three things before applying:
â” Your current code (what you wrote in .tf files).
â” Terraform state file (terraform.tfstate) â” (what Terraform believes already exists).
â” What we made changes will be in state
â” Real cloud resources â” (what actually exists in Azure, AWS, etc.).
When you run terraform plan:
â” It checks all three and shows the differences (what will be created, changed, or destroyed).
â— Saving the plan to a file (terraform plan -out=planfile) is helpful because:
â—‹ It locks the exact changes you reviewed.
â—‹ Later, you can apply exactly that without regenerating a new plan.
â—‹ Avoids surprises if the cloud or code changes in between plan and apply.
â—‹ when u create a rg for new ..this is compared with cloud - is it there or not
â—‹ if u apply create a state file(terraform.tfstate)
Q. why do u want state file?
â— Terraform can understand what u have done last time and compare with 3 things
Q. formatting the file and validate ?
â— formatting the file : terraform fmt
â— validate: terraform validate
Q. terraform destroy?
â” destroy : terraform destroy (a backup file created internally)
â” analyse and shows - i going to destroy this
â” alternative : delete from main.tf file
Q.Sonarqube?
â˜… Vulnerabilities: SonarQube can detect security vulnerabilities in your code, such as common
attacks (e.g., SQL injection).
â˜… Code Smells: Refers to bad code practices (not necessarily errors, but things that might cause
problems later).
â˜… Your Decision: You can accept or fix these issues based on your code quality standards.
Q. Availability Sets in Azure:
â˜… Fault Domain: Group of VMs that share a physical rack. If a hardware failure occurs in that
rack, the VMs in that fault domain are affected.
â˜… Update Domain: Group of VMs that are updated simultaneously. If there's an update to the
system, VMs in the same update domain are updated at the same time to avoid downtime.
